WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.830 --> 00:00:06.040
&gt;&gt;I want to open the floor. We have so many
smart and interesting people here and Michael

00:00:06.040 --> 00:00:09.940
Elliott was out there somewhere. Michael,
yeah you had a question I wanted to make sure

00:00:09.940 --> 00:00:12.421
I got it. And just identify, please identify
yourself - back there.

00:00:12.421 --> 00:00:20.900
MICHAEL: Hi, Mike Elliott from Time Magazine.
One of the unexpected, at least, to me, themes

00:00:20.900 --> 00:00:27.560
of the first day of Davos, yesterday, was
the crisis of expensive food that was mentioned

00:00:27.560 --> 00:00:34.430
by delegates from India, from Africa, and
from China. And rightly or wrongly, in many

00:00:34.430 --> 00:00:40.000
parts of the developing world that's associated
with the increasing amount of available corn

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:45.940
that's devoted to the production of Ethanol.
Similarly, Bono just earlier this morning

00:00:45.940 --> 00:00:53.730
pointed out that in landlocked parts of Africa
and other parts of the world, air transport

00:00:53.730 --> 00:00:59.480
is an essential tool of economic development.
I'd just like to ask all of you, how in practical

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:05.939
terms do you convince people in the developing
world that these two great goals [ INAUDIBLE

00:01:05.939 --> 00:01:11.920
 ] reduction and climate change are not in
conflict. I mean how do you convince people

00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:19.610
that climate change will not be a policy adopted
on the back of people who just recently have

00:01:19.610 --> 00:01:23.611
moved from one meal a day to two?

00:01:23.611 --> 00:01:27.420
Larry: Can I say I feel like, one of the biggest
problems we have in the world is people don't

00:01:27.420 --> 00:01:33.710
realize that technology is the way we solve
these problems so I was giving a talk recently

00:01:33.710 --> 00:01:39.730
and we have this great economist who helps
us out, Hal Varian, and I was saying, he's

00:01:39.730 --> 00:01:43.161
saying basically all the growth in GDP per
capita has been due to technology and you

00:01:43.161 --> 00:01:48.979
can graph it as like an exponential - you
know starts with basically farm improvements

00:01:48.979 --> 00:01:55.060
machinization and and mass manufacturing and
so on. And the way we're going to get out

00:01:55.060 --> 00:01:59.340
of problems like that is by having better
technology. And if you look at, you know the

00:01:59.340 --> 00:02:04.560
U.S. has something like, you have 10,000 people,
the equivalent of 10,000 people helping you

00:02:04.560 --> 00:02:09.890
every day with the energy use. They're pushing
your car, they're carrying your water up to

00:02:09.890 --> 00:02:14.510
you. If you work out the number of calories
you have to use as a person to do all the

00:02:14.510 --> 00:02:19.620
things that you do is something like 10,000
people. In Africa, that number is like one

00:02:19.620 --> 00:02:27.260
or two or zero. Right. And really, it's really
not fun to have to carry your water. It'd

00:02:27.260 --> 00:02:30.390
be really nice to have somebody carry your
water for you. And the way we're going to

00:02:30.390 --> 00:02:35.750
solve those problems is by having more energy
not less, and by having it not hurt our environment,

00:02:35.750 --> 00:02:41.380
the world that we live in. And by having it
be a lot cheaper, right. Having more, having

00:02:41.380 --> 00:02:44.881
it be cheaper, those things are related. The
way we're going to do that is with technology,

00:02:44.881 --> 00:02:50.284
we're not, there's no other magic that's going
to do it. And that's the way it's always been

00:02:50.284 --> 00:02:54.440
done and, if you look at the trends, there's
been huge, huge advances in all those things.

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:59.280
So I think the way you're going to solve the
poverty is by having helpers and energy is

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:04.720
a great way to have helpers. The food cost
is probably largely based on transportation.

00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:09.381
The cost of transportation is largely based
on the cost of energy. And so you know you

00:03:09.381 --> 00:03:14.250
solve, you'll solve both those problems at
once. You'll solve food and you'll solve energy

00:03:14.250 --> 00:03:18.930
and that'll help with poverty and starvation
and all those things. And the way we're going

00:03:18.930 --> 00:03:22.590
to do that is we're going to make it cheap
and prevalent and you know you can dig a whole

00:03:22.590 --> 00:03:27.500
anywhere in the world and get tons of energy.
That would be a great thing, right? Let's,

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:30.380
let's go build that.

00:03:30.380 --> 00:03:31.819
[ CROSS TALK ]

00:03:31.819 --> 00:03:37.810
&gt;&gt;What you just heard from Larry was what
I think forced me to change my mind about

00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:46.450
how you deal with climate change because the
logical extension of this faith, I think,

00:03:46.450 --> 00:03:51.700
in technology and engineering, not just faith
in the historical record of it. When we started

00:03:51.700 --> 00:03:55.580
doing out energy work, we were very interested
in renewables, we were interested in government

00:03:55.580 --> 00:04:03.590
policies. And Larry really challenged us.
He said you can't do it out of a feeling of

00:04:03.590 --> 00:04:09.610
scarcity. You can't react just out of conservation,
because then you won't have economic development

00:04:09.610 --> 00:04:14.840
and you will hurt so many people by any kind
of an abrupt slow down or any kind of trade

00:04:14.840 --> 00:04:18.939
off. You're absolutely right about the ethanol
issue. They're called chapote wars now or

00:04:18.939 --> 00:04:24.479
tortilla wars, because people are really rising
up against ethanol for that reason. But Larry

00:04:24.479 --> 00:04:29.970
says don't make it into a competition. He
says find a way to make electricity, not that

00:04:29.970 --> 00:04:34.620
you have to cut back on it, but that you have
more than you ever dreamed of and that you

00:04:34.620 --> 00:04:40.290
do it at prices less than you ever thought
of and gird your loins. Get the engineers

00:04:40.290 --> 00:04:43.710
LARRY: Wait. The corn issue is largely a policy
issue.

00:04:43.710 --> 00:04:44.710
&gt;&gt;Yeah.

00:04:44.710 --> 00:04:45.710
LARRY: I mean the reason corn as expensive
as it is because we're making ethanol out

00:04:45.710 --> 00:04:47.680
of it, which we should'nt be doing.

00:04:47.680 --> 00:04:48.680
&gt;&gt;Right.

00:04:48.680 --> 00:04:53.099
LARRY: And something I already mentioned we
have 50%, we have a 50 cent tariff in the

00:04:53.099 --> 00:04:59.159
U.S. on imported ethanol and a 50%, 50 cent
subsidy on corn ethanol. So it's a dollar

00:04:59.159 --> 00:05:03.110
a gallon, and that's why corn is expensive.
It's not, because people would otherwise be

00:05:03.110 --> 00:05:05.099
making ethanol out of corn.

00:05:05.099 --> 00:05:06.099
&gt;&gt;Right, right.

00:05:06.099 --> 00:05:11.750
&gt;&gt;It is a travesty that it there's a 54 cent
per gallon tariff if you want to import sugar

00:05:11.750 --> 00:05:17.210
ethanol from Brazil. But if you want to actually
import a gallon of refined gasoline from Saudi

00:05:17.210 --> 00:05:23.379
Arabia, it's only a penny and a half. So from
a country in our hemisphere that's a democracy,

00:05:23.379 --> 00:05:28.369
we have a 54 cent tariff and from the people
who brought us 911, we have a one cent and

00:05:28.369 --> 00:05:30.059
a half tariff. Al, please.

00:05:30.059 --> 00:05:35.490
&gt;&gt;Yeah, I wanted to briefly comment on Michael
Elliott's question. First of all I wanted

00:05:35.490 --> 00:05:44.840
to compliment the three of you for the equation
RE&lt;C. I think it's a brilliant and simple

00:05:44.840 --> 00:05:52.169
clarification of the key moving part in all
of this debate. But, there is actually a rich

00:05:52.169 --> 00:05:58.899
and growing literature on the connection between
food and security in the developing world

00:05:58.899 --> 00:06:07.819
and climate. And the price of tortillas and
the price of other staples has actually gone

00:06:07.819 --> 00:06:12.559
up more because of the thousand year drought
and what many are calling the thousand year

00:06:12.559 --> 00:06:19.710
drought in Australia and the effect on yields
on the supply side then on the very marginal

00:06:19.710 --> 00:06:25.249
extra pressure that comes from renewable [ INAUDIBLE
 ]. I happen to agree that corn-based ethanol

00:06:25.249 --> 00:06:33.729
is just a transition dead end towards cellulosic
ethanol and the use of enzymes, enzymatic

00:06:33.729 --> 00:06:41.319
hydrolysis is what I think above my pay grade
but it's I think one of the winners on this.

00:06:41.319 --> 00:06:48.330
But if you look at the map of where the food
is to be grown in the developing world, the

00:06:48.330 --> 00:06:54.189
impact of the climate on this is by far the
most important issue. The United Nations Development

00:06:54.189 --> 00:06:59.949
Program has put out two reports now, Kevin
Watkins, the principle author says that climate

00:06:59.949 --> 00:07:08.189
is the principle development challenge. And
the program for fighting against food insecurity

00:07:08.189 --> 00:07:17.729
has to take account of climate in order to
succeed. And by the way, the trends in agriculture

00:07:17.729 --> 00:07:23.199
in developing the poorest of the poor countries,
has been mono-culture. The reason why as Larry

00:07:23.199 --> 00:07:28.039
Brilliant said the highest percentage of jobs
is with the large multi-nationals is because

00:07:28.039 --> 00:07:33.419
they're replacing the kind of subsistence
agriculture with locally grown appropriate

00:07:33.419 --> 00:07:42.240
crops, with these huge plantations of mono-culture
that depend upon lots of petroleum, lots of

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:49.289
transportation. Wangari Maathai's Green Belt
program got it's notice for tree planting,

00:07:49.289 --> 00:08:00.580
but she uses that to educate women primarily
to go back to the traditional crops that are,

00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:05.550
and you know Alice Waters in the United States
has been among those who's generated this

00:08:05.550 --> 00:08:12.009
movement. Food and security is one of the
principle cutting edges of the climate crisis

00:08:12.009 --> 00:08:19.240
in the developing world and solving it is
yet another reason why we have to intertwine

00:08:19.240 --> 00:08:28.580
this with solutions of the climate crisis.
One final point. Back to the Re&lt;C. Innovators

00:08:28.580 --> 00:08:36.390
bringing renewable energy down in cost represents
the left-hand side of that equation. The right-hand

00:08:36.390 --> 00:08:41.660
side of the equation is equally important.
The extraordnalities that are not presently

00:08:41.660 --> 00:08:47.460
reflected in the price of coal and fossil
fuels, have to be priced into this equation

00:08:47.460 --> 00:08:55.000
but in order to reflect reality. And rather
than seeing that as a tax, it should be seen

00:08:55.000 --> 00:09:01.550
as a revenue swap. That all ought to come
back on the left-hand side of the equation

00:09:01.550 --> 00:09:07.180
and in the form of adaptation, not only in
the poorest of the poor countries, but among

00:09:07.180 --> 00:09:09.190
the poorest of the poor in the rich countries.

00:09:09.190 --> 00:09:11.500
&gt;&gt;Thank you.

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:12.500
[ CROSS TALK ]

00:09:12.500 --> 00:09:18.640
&gt;&gt;Can I just make a very quick comment? Judy
Rodin is here who runs the Rockerfeller Foundation

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:23.960
and she's sort of been our inspiration and
mentor. They have $150,000,000 program, the

00:09:23.960 --> 00:09:30.000
AGRA Program, which is to try to deal with
new seeds, Gates puts them, most, two thirds

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:35.620
of the money in. That is because Africa never
really had a green revolution, not in the

00:09:35.620 --> 00:09:41.470
way we think of India having had one, and
because of climate change you will see intercurrent

00:09:41.470 --> 00:09:47.800
drought and floods and salinity as salt is
brought from the rising seas over the shores

00:09:47.800 --> 00:09:53.610
and the agricultural land. The situation is
so dire that for the first time in known history,

00:09:53.610 --> 00:09:58.300
farmers in Andhra Pradesh and in parts of
India are committing suicide, because their

00:09:58.300 --> 00:10:04.340
lands will no longer produce enough calories
per actor to feed their family. So Al, in

00:10:04.340 --> 00:10:10.660
my experience is actually right. These are
twins of the same problem climate change makes

00:10:10.660 --> 00:10:16.100
poverty worse. Poverty, if it does economic
development the wrong way makes climate change

00:10:16.100 --> 00:10:19.970
worse. We can't choose sides. We have to be
both and.

00:10:19.970 --> 00:10:20.970
&gt;&gt;Yes there.

00:10:20.970 --> 00:10:25.970
&gt;&gt;Yeah, thanks I want to add one other thing
to this both and. I don't know whether to

00:10:25.970 --> 00:10:31.240
challenge Larry Brilliant or to ask a leading
question of Sergey and Larry, but none of

00:10:31.240 --> 00:10:39.320
this, if you think the U.S. government is
short-sighted, the other governments are so

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:45.019
much worse that there is a huge amount of
corruption in many of these countries and

00:10:45.019 --> 00:10:49.950
it forestalls things. You can have business
plans up the wazoo, but now your guy gets

00:10:49.950 --> 00:10:56.270
his $50,000 and the next thing you know the
tax inspector comes calling. Or he tries to

00:10:56.270 --> 00:11:02.540
open an office, but it gets closed down because
some rich land owner who's related to the

00:11:02.540 --> 00:11:07.920
nephew of the governor wants to start a shopping
mall or something like that. And so, in order

00:11:07.920 --> 00:11:13.720
for the top down stuff to happen, you just
need to go talk to the governments, but for

00:11:13.720 --> 00:11:20.300
most of the bottom up stuff to happen, the
stuff that's going to create the diversity

00:11:20.300 --> 00:11:24.060
and the props and the entrepreneurs and all
this economic growth. One way or another you

00:11:24.060 --> 00:11:28.850
do have to take on these governments. Please
comment.

00:11:28.850 --> 00:11:35.181
Larry: Well I actually, Larry and I have been
talking about this issue a lot. I spent some

00:11:35.181 --> 00:11:41.260
time actually in Ethiopia in the elections
actually with the Carter Center just monitoring

00:11:41.260 --> 00:11:47.470
the elections, which was really interesting
I recommend that to people, and they have

00:11:47.470 --> 00:11:51.110
really good systems, I mean you can debate
the election there but they have really good

00:11:51.110 --> 00:11:54.790
systems now for they have series of like 10
rules before they'll go in

00:11:54.790 --> 00:11:57.250
&gt;&gt;It was all Larry's fault, he miscounted.

00:11:57.250 --> 00:11:58.250
[ LAUGHTER ]

00:11:58.250 --> 00:12:03.500
Larry: [ INAUDIBLE ] like they have for example
10 things they have to have before they go

00:12:03.500 --> 00:12:11.970
into a country to monitor elections. And,
for example the U.S. meets none of them, by

00:12:11.970 --> 00:12:15.070
the way, whereas many, most of the countries
 [ INAUDIBLE ] countries during elections

00:12:15.070 --> 00:12:19.220
do meet those. And, you know, it's just about
accountability, you know they, everybody watches

00:12:19.220 --> 00:12:26.280
the ballot box getting filled, the ballot
